answers.body_markdown:
You should parse the int as the value is getting read from the event.target.value which will always give you string

      handleChange = (e) =&gt; {
        const { name, value } = e.target
        this.setState({ [name]: parseInt(value, 10) })
      }

You can use `parseInt` when use the setState:

```javascript
  handleChange = (e) =&gt; {
    const { name, value } = e.target
    this.setState({ [name]: parseInt(value) })
  }
```

But maybe is necessary to valid the value before execute parseInt, because can happen a error like `Received NaN for the `value` attribute. If this is expected, cast the value to a string.`

So maybe with `try/catch` can solve your problem:

```javascript
  handleChange = (e) =&gt; {
    const { name, value } = e.target

    try {
      this.setState({ [name]: parseInt(value) })
    } catch (e) {
      this.setState({ [name]: 0})
    }
  }
```

